<li><figure-inline class="noviewer" typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Dharma_Wheel.svg"><img resource="./File:Dharma_Wheel.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Dharma_Wheel.svg/16px-Dharma_Wheel.svg.png" data-file-width="690" data-file-height="690" data-file-type="drawing" height="16" width="16" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Dharma_Wheel.svg/32px-Dharma_Wheel.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Dharma_Wheel.svg/24px-Dharma_Wheel.svg.png 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Portal:Buddhism" title="Portal:Buddhism">Buddhism<span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span>portal</a></li></ul></td></tr><tr><td style="text-align:right;font-size:115%;padding-top: 0.6em;"><div class="plainlinks hlist navbar mini"><ul><li class="nv-view"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Template:Buddhism" title="Template:Buddhism"><abbr title="View this template">v</abbr></a></li><li class="nv-talk"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Template_talk:Buddhism" title="Template talk:Buddhism"><abbr title="Discuss this template">t</abbr></a></li><li class="nv-edit"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Buddhism&amp;action=edit"><abbr title="Edit this template">e</abbr></a></li></ul></div></td></tr></tbody></table>

<p id="mwGQ"><b id="mwGg">Theravāda</b> (<span class="nowrap" about="#mwt16" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"IPAc-en","href":"./Template:IPAc-en"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"ˌ"},"2":{"wt":"t"},"3":{"wt":"ɛr"},"4":{"wt":"ə"},"5":{"wt":"ˈ"},"6":{"wt":"v"},"7":{"wt":"ɑː"},"8":{"wt":"d"},"9":{"wt":"ə"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwGw"><span class="IPA nopopups noexcerpt"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Help:IPA/English" title="Help:IPA/English">/<span style="border-bottom:1px dotted"><span title="/ˌ/: secondary stress follows">ˌ</span><span title="'t' in 'tie'">t</span><span title="/ɛr/: 'err' in 'merry'">ɛr</span><span title="/ə/: 'a' in 'about'">ə</span><span title="/ˈ/: primary stress follows">ˈ</span><span title="'v' in 'vie'">v</span><span title="/ɑː/: 'a' in 'father'">ɑː</span><span title="'d' in 'dye'">d</span><span title="/ə/: 'a' in 'about'">ə</span></span>/</a></span></span>; <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Pali" title="Pali" id="mwHA">Pāli</a>, lit. "School of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Thero" title="Thero" id="mwHQ">Elders</a>"<sup about="#mwt291" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-Bodhi_1-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"Bodhi"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-Bodhi-1"}}'><a href="./Theravada#cite_note-Bodhi-1" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 1;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[1]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt293" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-Britannica_2-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"Britannica"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-Britannica-2"}}'><a href="./Theravada#cite_note-Britannica-2" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 2;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[2]</span></a></sup>) is the most ancient branch of extant <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Buddhism" title="Buddhism" id="mwHg">Buddhism</a> today,<sup about="#mwt20" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-Bodhi_1-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"Bodhi"}}'><a href="./Theravada#cite_note-Bodhi-1" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 1;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[1]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt22" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-Britannica_2-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"Britannica"}}'><a href="./Theravada#cite_note-Britannica-2" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 2;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[2]</span></a></sup> and the one that preserved their version of the teachings of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Gautama_Buddha" title="Gautama Buddha" id="mwHw">Gautama Buddha</a> in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Pāli_Canon" title="Pāli Canon" id="mwIA">Pāli Canon</a>.<sup about="#mwt24" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-Bodhi_1-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"Bodhi"}}'><a href="./Theravada#cite_note-Bodhi-1" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 1;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[1]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt26" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-Britannica_2-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"Britannica"}}'><a href="./Theravada#cite_note-Britannica-2" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 2;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[2]</span></a></sup> The Pāli Canon is the only complete Buddhist canon which survives in a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Indo-Aryan_languages" title="Indo-Aryan languages" id="mwIQ">classical Indian language</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Pali" title="Pali" id="mwIg">Pāli</a>, which serves as both <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sacred_language" title="Sacred language" id="mwIw">sacred language</a><sup about="#mwt28" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-Britannica_2-3" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"Britannica"}}'><a href="./Theravada#cite_note-Britannica-2" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 2;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[2]</span></a></sup> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lingua_franca" title="Lingua franca" id="mwJA">lingua franca</a> of Theravāda Buddhism.<sup about="#mwt34" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-Crosby,_Kate_2013_p._2_3-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"Crosby, Kate 2013 p. 2"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-Crosby,_Kate_2013_p._2-3"}}'><a href="./Theravada#cite_note-Crosby,_Kate_2013_p._2-3" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 3;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[3]</span></a></sup> For more than a millennium, Theravāda has focused on preserving the <i id="mwJQ">dhamma</i> as preserved in its texts,<sup about="#mwt30" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-Braun2014_4-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"group":"web","name":"Braun2014"}}'><a href="./Theravada#cite_note-Braun2014-4" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 1;" data-mw-group="web"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[web 1]</span></a></sup> and it tends to be very conservative with regard to matters of doctrine and monastic discipline.<sup about="#mwt36" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-5" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-5"}}'><a href="./Theravada#cite_note-5" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 4;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[4]</span></a></sup> Since the 19th century, meditation practice has been re-introduced, and has become popular with a lay audience, both in traditional Theravada countries and in the west.<sup about="#mwt32" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-Braun2014_4-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"group":"web","name":"Braun2014"}}'><a href="./Theravada#cite_note-Braun2014-4" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 1;" data-mw-group="web"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[web 1]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwJg">As a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Early_Buddhist_schools" title="Early Buddhist schools" id="mwJw">distinct school of early Buddhism</a>, Theravāda Buddhism developed in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sri_Lanka" title="Sri Lanka" id="mwKA">Sri Lanka</a> and subsequently <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Buddhism_in_Southeast_Asia" title="Buddhism in Southeast Asia" id="mwKQ">spread to the rest of Southeast Asia</a>. It is the dominant form of religion in Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar, Sri Lanka, and Thailand, and is practiced by minority groups in India, Bangladesh, China, Nepal, and Vietnam. In addition, the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Diaspora" title="Diaspora" id="mwKg">diaspora</a> of all of these groups as well as converts around the world practice Theravāda Buddhism. Contemporary expressions include <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Buddhist_modernism" title="Buddhist modernism" id="mwKw">Buddhist modernism</a>, the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vipassana_movement" title="Vipassana movement" id="mwLA">Vipassana movement</a>, and the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Thai_Forest_Tradition" title="Thai Forest Tradition" id="mwLQ">Thai Forest Tradition</a>.</p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="1" id="mwLg"><h2 id="Ambiguity">Ambiguity</h2>
<p id="mwLw">Although the term "Theravāda" means <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sthaviravāda" title="Sthaviravāda" id="mwMA" class="mw-redirect">Sthaviravāda</a>, Theravada descends from the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tāmraparṇīya" title="Tāmraparṇīya" id="mwMQ" class="new">Tāmraparṇīya sect</a> of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vibhajyavāda" title="Vibhajyavāda" id="mwMg">Vibhajyavāda</a> Sthaviravāda which rejects the idea of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Bodhisattvayāna" title="Bodhisattvayāna" id="mwMw" class="mw-redirect">"two yānas"</a> favored by the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dharmaguptaka" title="Dharmaguptaka" id="mwNA">Dharmaguptaka sect</a> of Vibhajyavāda Sthaviravāda. Theravāda is a subset of Sthaviravāda and Sthaviravāda also includes some schools that give rise to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mahayana_Buddhist" title="Mahayana Buddhist" id="mwNQ" class="mw-redirect">Mahayana Buddhist</a> ideas. Theravada has focused on preserving the ancient Sthaviravāda idea of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Śrāvaka" title="Śrāvaka" id="mwNg">Śrāvaka</a> path and doctrine, that distinguishes them from Dharmaguptaka and Sarvāstivāda school which have since become extinct. The <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sarvāstivāda" title="Sarvāstivāda" id="mwNw" class="mw-redirect">Sarvāstivāda</a> Sthaviravāda school is an important contributor of early Chinese schools of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mahayana_Buddhism" title="Mahayana Buddhism" id="mwOA" class="mw-redirect">Mahayana Buddhism</a> and Tibetan schools of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vajrayana_Buddhism" title="Vajrayana Buddhism" id="mwOQ" class="mw-redirect">Vajrayana Buddhism</a>.</p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="2" id="mwOg"><h2 id="History">History</h2>

<section data-mw-section-id="3" id="mwOw"><h3 id="Origins">Origins</h3>
<figure typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwPA"><a href="./File:Nava_Jetavana_Temple_-_Shravasti_-_014_King_Asoka_at_the_Third_Council_(9241725897).jpg" id="mwPQ"><img resource="./File:Nava_Jetavana_Temple_-_Shravasti_-_014_King_Asoka_at_the_Third_Council_(9241725897).jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/33/Nava_Jetavana_Temple_-_Shravasti_-_014_King_Asoka_at_the_Third_Council_%289241725897%29.jpg/300px-Nava_Jetavana_Temple_-_Shravasti_-_014_King_Asoka_at_the_Third_Council_%289241725897%29.jpg" data-file-width="3021" data-file-height="1811" data-file-type="bitmap" height="180" width="300" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/33/Nava_Jetavana_Temple_-_Shravasti_-_014_King_Asoka_at_the_Third_Council_%289241725897%29.jpg/600px-Nava_Jetavana_Temple_-_Shravasti_-_014_King_Asoka_at_the_Third_Council_%289241725897%29.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/33/Nava_Jetavana_Temple_-_Shravasti_-_014_King_Asoka_at_the_Third_Council_%289241725897%29.jpg/450px-Nava_Jetavana_Temple_-_Shravasti_-_014_King_Asoka_at_the_Third_Council_%289241725897%29.jpg 1.5x" id="mwPg"/></a><figcaption id="mwPw"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ashoka" title="Ashoka" id="mwQA">Ashoka</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Moggaliputta-Tissa" title="Moggaliputta-Tissa" id="mwQQ">Moggaliputta-Tissa</a> at the Third Council, at the Nava Jetavana, Shravasti</figcaption></figure>
<table class="vertical-navbox nowraplinks" style="float:right;clear:right;width:22.0em;margin:0 0 1.0em 1.0em;background:#f9f9f9;border:1px solid #aaa;padding:0.2em;border-spacing:0.4em 0;text-align:center;line-height:1.4em;font-size:88%" about="#mwt37" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"EarlyBuddhism","href":"./Template:EarlyBuddhism"},"params":{},"i":0}}]}' id="mwQg"><tbody><tr><td style="padding:0.4em 0"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Sanchi_Great_Stupa_under_the_Sungas.jpg"><img resource="./File:Sanchi_Great_Stupa_under_the_Sungas.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Sanchi_Great_Stupa_under_the_Sungas.jpg/150px-Sanchi_Great_Stupa_under_the_Sungas.jpg" data-file-width="1186" data-file-height="506" data-file-type="bitmap" height="64" width="150" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Sanchi_Great_Stupa_under_the_Sungas.jpg/300px-Sanchi_Great_Stupa_under_the_Sungas.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Sanchi_Great_Stupa_under_the_Sungas.jpg/225px-Sanchi_Great_Stupa_under_the_Sungas.jpg 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline></td></tr><tr><th style="padding:0.2em 0.4em 0.2em;font-size:145%;line-height:1.2em"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Early_Buddhism" title="Early Buddhism">Early Buddhism</a></th></tr><tr><td style="padding:0 0.1em 0.4em">
