"wt":"Giuseppe"},"author-link5":{"wt":"Giuseppe Tucci"},"date":{"wt":"2018"},"website":{"wt":"britannica.com"},"publisher":{"wt":"&apos;&apos;[[Encyclopaedia Britannica]]&apos;&apos;"},"quote":{"wt":"Theravada (Pali: “Way of the Elders”; Sanskrit, Sthaviravada) emerged as one of the [[Hinayana]] (Sanskrit: “Lesser Vehicle”) [[Early Buddhist schools|schools]], traditionally numbered at 18, of early Buddhism. The Theravadins trace their lineage to the [[Sthavira nikāya|Sthaviravada]] school, one of the two major schools (the [[Mahāsāṃghika|Mahasanghika]] was the other) that supposedly formed in the wake of the [[Second Buddhist council|Council of Vaishali]] (now in [[Bihar|Bihar state]]) held some 100 years after the Buddha’s death. Employing Pali as their sacred language, the Theravadins preserved their version of the Buddha’s teaching in the &apos;&apos;[[Tipitaka]]&apos;&apos; (“Three Baskets”)."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBgg">Reynolds, Frank E.; Kitagawa, Joseph M.; <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Hajime_Nakamura" title="Hajime Nakamura" id="mwBgk">Nakamura, Hajime</a>; <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Donald_S._Lopez_Jr." title="Donald S. Lopez Jr." id="mwBgo">Lopez, Donald S.</a>; <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Giuseppe_Tucci" title="Giuseppe Tucci" id="mwBgs">Tucci, Giuseppe</a> (2018). <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Buddhism/Historical-development" id="mwBgw">"Theravada"</a>. <i id="mwBg0">britannica.com</i>. <i id="mwBg4"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Encyclopaedia_Britannica" title="Encyclopaedia Britannica" id="mwBg8" class="mw-redirect">Encyclopaedia Britannica</a></i>. <q id="mwBhA">Theravada (Pali: “Way of the Elders”; Sanskrit, Sthaviravada) emerged as one of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Hinayana" title="Hinayana" id="mwBhE">Hinayana</a> (Sanskrit: “Lesser Vehicle”) <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Early_Buddhist_schools" title="Early Buddhist schools" id="mwBhI">schools</a>, traditionally numbered at 18, of early Buddhism. The Theravadins trace their lineage to the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sthavira_nikāya" title="Sthavira nikāya" id="mwBhM">Sthaviravada</a> school, one of the two major schools (the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mahāsāṃghika" title="Mahāsāṃghika" id="mwBhQ">Mahasanghika</a> was the other) that supposedly formed in the wake of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Second_Buddhist_council" title="Second Buddhist council" id="mwBhU">Council of Vaishali</a> (now in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Bihar" title="Bihar" id="mwBhY">Bihar state</a>) held some 100 years after the Buddha’s death. Employing Pali as their sacred language, the Theravadins preserved their version of the Buddha’s teaching in the <i id="mwBhc"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tipitaka" title="Tipitaka" id="mwBhg" class="mw-redirect">Tipitaka</a></i> (“Three Baskets”).</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=britannica.com&amp;rft.atitle=Theravada&amp;rft.date=2018&amp;rft.aulast=Reynolds&amp;rft.aufirst=Frank+E.&amp;rft.au=Kitagawa%2C+Joseph+M.&amp;rft.au=Nakamura%2C+Hajime&amp;rft.au=Lopez%2C+Donald+S.&amp;rft.au=Tucci%2C+Giuseppe&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.britannica.com%2Ftopic%2FBuddhism%2FHistorical-development&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATheravada" class="Z3988" about="#mwt18" id="mwBhk"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt18" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwBho"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-Crosby,_Kate_2013_p._2-3" id="cite_note-Crosby,_Kate_2013_p._2-3"><span rel="mw:referencedBy"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-Crosby,_Kate_2013_p._2_3-0"><span class="mw-linkback-text">1 </span></a><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-Crosby,_Kate_2013_p._2_3-1"><span class="mw-linkback-text">2 </span></a></span> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-Crosby,_Kate_2013_p._2-3" class="mw-reference-text">Crosby, Kate (2013), <i id="mwBhs">Theravada Buddhism: Continuity, Diversity, and Identity</i>, p. 2.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-5" id="cite_note-5"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-5" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-5" class="mw-reference-text"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Richard_Gombrich" title="Richard Gombrich" id="mwBhw">Gombrich, Richard</a> (2006), <i id="mwBh0">Theravada Buddhism: A Social History from Ancient Benares to Modern Colombo</i>, Routledge; 2nd edition, p. 37.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-7" id="cite_note-7"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-7" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-7" class="mw-reference-text">Skilton, Andrew. <i id="mwBh4">A Concise History of Buddhism.</i> 2004. p. 49, 64</span></li><li about="#cite_note-8" id="cite_note-8"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-8" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-8" class="mw-reference-text">Cousins, Lance (2001). "<a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://journals.equinoxpub.com/index.php/BSR/article/view/8772/6247" id="mwBh8">On the Vibhajjavādins</a>", Buddhist Studies Review 18 (2), 131–182</span></li><li about="#cite_note-9" id="cite_note-9"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-9" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-9" class="mw-reference-text">Keown, Damien. <i id="mwBiA">A Dictionary of Buddhism.</i> 2003. <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt44" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"ISBN","href":"./Template:ISBN"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"0-19-860560-9"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBiE"/><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Sta