<li about="#cite_note-126" id="cite_note-126"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-126" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-126" class="mw-reference-text">James P. McDermott, <i id="mwBrY">Encyclopedia of Indian Philosophies</i>, Volume VII: Abhidharma Buddhism to 150 A.D. p. 95</span></li><li about="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWarder2000284-127" id="cite_note-FOOTNOTEWarder2000284-127"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWarder2000284_127-0" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-FOOTNOTEWarder2000284-127" class="mw-reference-text"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Theravada#CITEREFWarder2000" id="mwBrc">Warder 2000</a>, p.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwBrg"> </span>284.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-128" id="cite_note-128"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-128" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-128" class="mw-reference-text"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./K._L._Dhammajoti" title="K. L. Dhammajoti" id="mwBrk">K. L. Dhammajoti</a>, Sarvāstivāda Abhidharma, p. 66</span></li><li about="#cite_note-:2-129" id="cite_note-:2-129"><span rel="mw:referencedBy"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-:2_129-0"><span class="mw-linkback-text">1 </span></a><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-:2_129-1"><span class="mw-linkback-text">2 </span></a><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-:2_129-2"><span class="mw-linkback-text">3 </span></a></span> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-:2-129" class="mw-reference-text">Ronkin, Noa, Early Buddhist Metaphysics: The Making of a Philosophical Tradition (Routledge curzon Critical Studies in Buddhism) 2011, p. 62.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-130" id="cite_note-130"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-130" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-130" class="mw-reference-text">Wayman, Alex, Buddhist Insight: Essays, Motilal Banarsidass Publ., 1984 p. 252</span></li><li about="#cite_note-131" id="cite_note-131"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-131" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-131" class="mw-reference-text">Langer, Rita, Buddhist Rituals of Death and Rebirth: Contemporary Sri Lankan Practice and Its Origins, 2007, p. 82</span></li><li about="#cite_note-shin-ibs.edu-132" id="cite_note-shin-ibs.edu-132"><span rel="mw:referencedBy"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-shin-ibs.edu_132-0"><span class="mw-linkback-text">1 </span></a><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-shin-ibs.edu_132-1"><span class="mw-linkback-text">2 </span></a></span> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-shin-ibs.edu-132" class="mw-reference-text"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20150226091354/http://www.shin-ibs.edu/documents/bForum/v3/02Gethin.pdf" id="mwBro">Gethin, Bhavaṅga and Rebirth According to the Abhidhamma</a></span></li><li about="#cite_note-:12-133" id="cite_note-:12-133"><span rel="mw:referencedBy"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-:12_133-0"><span class="mw-linkback-text">1 </span></a><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-:12_133-1"><span class="mw-linkback-text">2 </span></a><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-:12_133-2"><span class="mw-linkback-text">3 </span></a></span> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-:12-133" class="mw-reference-text">Harvey, Peter; The mind-body relationship in Pali Buddhism: A philosophical investigation, Asian Philosophy, Vol. 3 No. 1 1993, pp. 29–41</span></li><li about="#cite_note-134" id="cite_note-134"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-134" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-134" class="mw-reference-text">Karunadasa, Y. Buddhist Analysis of Matter, p. 169.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-135" id="cite_note-135"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-135" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-135" class="mw-reference-text">Karunadasa, Y. Buddhist Analysis of Matter, pp. 14, 172; "If we base ourselves on the Pali Nikayas, then we should be compelled to conclude that Buddhism is realistic. There is no explicit denial anywhere of the external world. Nor is there any positive evidence to show that the world is mind-made or simply a projection of subjective thoughts. That Buddhism recognizes the extra-mental existence of matter and the external world is clearly suggested by the texts. Throughout the discourses it is the language of realism that one encounters. The whole Buddhist practical doctrine and discipline, which has the attainment of Nibbana as its final goal, is based on the recognition of the material world and the conscious living beings living therein."</span></li><li about="#cite_note-136" id="cite_note-136"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-136" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-136" class="mw-reference-text">Karunadasa, Y. Buddhist Analysis of Matter, p. 175.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-Ronkin,_Noa_page_58-137" id="cite_note-Ronkin,_Noa_page_58-137"><span rel="mw:referencedBy"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-Ronkin,_Noa_page_58_137-0"><span class="mw-linkback-text">1 </span></a><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-Ronkin,_Noa_page_58_137-1"><span class="mw-linkback-text">2 </span></a></span> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-Ronkin,_Noa_page_58-137" class="mw-reference-text">Ronkin, Noa; <i id="mwBrs">Early Buddhist Metaphysics</i>, p. 58.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-Swearer,_Donald_K_p._164-138" id="cite_note-Swearer,_Donald_K_p._164-138"><span rel="mw:referencedBy"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-Swearer,_Donald_K_p._164_138-0"><span class="mw-linkback-text">1 </span></a><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-Swearer,_Donald_K_p._164_138-1"><span class="mw-linkback-text">2 </span></a></span> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-Swearer,_Donald_K_p._164-138" class="mw-reference-text">Swearer, Donald K. The Buddhist World of Southeast Asia: Second Edition, p. 164.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-139" id="cite_note-139"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-139" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-139" class="mw-reference-text">McMahan, David L. 2008. The Making of Buddhist Modernism. Oxford: Oxford University Press. pp. 91–97.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-142" id="cite_note-142"><a href="./Theravada#cite_ref-142" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-142" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation web" about="#mwt680" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite web","href":"./Template:Cite_web"},"params":{"url":{"wt":"http://dsal.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/philologic/getobject.pl?c.2:1:989.pali"},"title":{"wt":"The Pali Text Society&apos;s Pali-English dictionary"},"date":{"wt":""},"publisher":{"wt":"Dsal.uchicago.edu"},"archive-url":{"wt":"https://archive.is/20120708071648/http://dsal.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/philologic/getobject.pl?c.2:1:989.pali"},"archive-date":{"wt":"2012-07-08"},"dead-url":{"wt":"yes"},"accessdate":{"wt":"2012-08-17"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBrw"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://archive.is/20120708071648/http://dsal.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/philologic/getobject.pl?c.2:1:989.pali" id="mwBr0">"The Pali Text Society's Pali-English dictionary"</a>. Dsal.uchicago.edu. Archived from <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://dsal.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/philologic/getobject.pl?c.2:1:989.pali" id="mwBr4">the original</a> on 2012-07-08<span class="reference-accessdate" id="mwBr8">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap" id="mwBsA">2012-08-17</span></span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=The+Pali+Text+Society%27s+Pali-English+dictiona